06524nam a22010335i 9783110212815DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20092009gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)719449753  a97831102128157 a10.1515/97831102128152doi  a(DE-B1597)35682  a(OCoLC)558838708  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aBS1525.52b.P74 2009eb 7aREL0060902bisacsh04a224/.20622200aProphecy in the Book of Jeremiah /ced. by Hans M. Barstad, Reinhard G. Kratz. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (289 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBeihefte zur Zeitschrift für die alttestamentliche Wissenschaft ,x0934-2575 ;v3880 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume contains the proceedings of a Symposium “Prophecy in the Book of Jeremiah”, arranged by the Edinburgh Prophecy Network in the School of Divinity at the University of Edinburgh, 11–12 May 2007. Prophetic studies are undergoing radical changes at the moment, following the breakdown of a methodological consensus in humanities and biblical studies. One of the challenges today concerns the question how to deal with history in a “post-modern” age. The French Annales School and narrative theory have contributed toward changing the intellectual climate of biblical studies dramatically. Whereas the “historical Jeremiah” was formerly believed to be hidden under countless additions and interpretations, and changed beyond recognition, it was still assumed that it would be possible to recover the “real” prophet with the tools of historical critical methods. However, according to a majority of scholars today, the recovery of the historical Jeremiah is no longer possible. For this reason, we have to seek new and multimethodological approaches to the study of prophecy, including diachronic and synchronic methods. The Meeting in Edinburgh in 2007 gathered specialists in prophetic studies from Denmark, Finland, Germany, the Netherlands, United Kingdom and the USA, focusing on different aspects of the prophet Jeremiah. Prophetic texts from the whole Hebrew Bible and ancient Near Eastern prophecy are taken into consideration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 4aJeremia (Buch). 4aProphezeiung. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / Old Testament.2bisacsh  aJeremiah.  aProphecy.1 aAuld, Graeme, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarstad, Hans M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarstad, Hans M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBecking, Bob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBezzel, Hannes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBultmann, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrabbe, Lester L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayes, Elizabeth R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKratz, Reinhard G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNissinen, Martti, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReimer, David J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchaper, Joachim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStipp, Hermann‐Josef, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThelle, Rannfrid I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTiemeyer, Lena‐Sofia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeeks, Stuart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eB